    <section class="section">
      <h2>How to Choose: Beginner Checklist</h2>
      <div class="grid">
        <article class="card">
          <h3>1. Autofocus is King</h3>
          <p>Don't look at megapixels first. Look at autofocus. A camera that can automatically lock onto an eye
            (Eye-AF) ensures your portraits are sharp 99% of the time, letting you focus on composition.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <h3>2. The Lens Trap</h3>
          <p>A camera body is only as good as its lenses. Sony (E-mount) has the most cheap functionality options. Canon
            (RF) is great but proprietary/expensive. Fuji (X-mount) is excellent for primes.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <h3>3. Viewfinder vs Screen</h3>
          <p>If you shoot outdoors in bright sun, you NEED a viewfinder (EVF) like on the Canon R50 or Fuji X-T50. If
            you mostly shoot video or indoors, a screen-only camera like the ZV-E10 II is fine.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

